WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.240
The following is a conversation with Richard Rangham,

00:03.240 --> 00:05.720
a biological anthropologist at Harvard,

00:05.720 --> 00:08.240
specializing in the study of primates

00:08.240 --> 00:12.200
and the evolution of violence, sex, cooking, culture,

00:12.200 --> 00:15.160
and other aspects of ape and human behavior

00:15.160 --> 00:18.360
at the individual and societal level.

00:18.360 --> 00:20.960
He began his career over four decades ago

00:20.960 --> 00:22.320
working with Jane Goodall

00:22.320 --> 00:24.560
and studying the behavior of chimps.

00:24.560 --> 00:27.320
And since then, has done a lot of seminal work

00:27.320 --> 00:28.640
on human evolution

00:28.800 --> 00:30.840
and has proposed several theories

00:30.840 --> 00:33.480
for the roles of fire and violence

00:33.480 --> 00:36.680
in the evolution of us, hairless apes,

00:36.680 --> 00:39.560
otherwise known as homo sapiens.

00:39.560 --> 00:41.760
This is the Lex Friedman podcast.

00:41.760 --> 00:43.600
To support it, please check out our sponsors

00:43.600 --> 00:44.960
in the description.

00:44.960 --> 00:49.040
And now, here's my conversation with Richard Rangham.

00:50.080 --> 00:53.160
You've said that we are much less violent

00:53.160 --> 00:57.080
than our close living relatives, the chimps.

00:57.080 --> 01:01.040
Can you elaborate on this point of how violent we are

01:01.040 --> 01:04.560
and how violent our evolutionary relatives are?

01:04.560 --> 01:06.040
Well, I haven't said exactly

01:06.040 --> 01:08.000
that we're less violent than chimps.

01:08.000 --> 01:11.320
What I've said is that there are two kinds of violence.

01:11.320 --> 01:13.320
One stems from proactive aggression

01:13.320 --> 01:15.640
and the other stems from reactive aggression.

01:15.640 --> 01:17.880
Proactive aggression is planned aggression.

01:17.880 --> 01:20.800
Reactive aggression is impulsive, defensive.

01:20.800 --> 01:24.600
It's reactive because it takes place

01:24.600 --> 01:26.880
in seconds after the threat.

01:28.000 --> 01:30.920
And the thing that is really striking about humans

01:30.920 --> 01:33.840
compared to our close relatives

01:33.840 --> 01:38.840
is the great reduction in the degree of reactive aggression.

01:40.280 --> 01:43.240
So we are far less violent than chimps

01:43.240 --> 01:46.760
when prompted by some relatively minor threat

01:46.760 --> 01:48.680
within our own society.

01:48.680 --> 01:53.680
And the way I judge that is with not super satisfactory data,

01:54.520 --> 01:59.520
but the study which is particularly striking

01:59.520 --> 02:04.520
is one of people living as hunter-gatherers

02:05.240 --> 02:09.760
in a really upsetting kind of environment,

02:09.760 --> 02:14.760
namely people in Australia living in a place

02:15.360 --> 02:19.200
where they got a lot of alcohol abuse.

02:19.200 --> 02:21.560
There's a lot of domestic violence.

02:21.800 --> 02:26.800
It's all a sort of a society that is as bad

02:29.240 --> 02:30.560
from the point of view of violence

02:30.560 --> 02:33.160
as an ordinary society can get.

02:34.200 --> 02:36.960
There's excellent data on the frequency

02:36.960 --> 02:39.240
with which people actually have physical violence

02:39.240 --> 02:40.440
and hit each other.

02:40.440 --> 02:45.080
And we can compare that to data from several different sites

02:45.080 --> 02:50.080
comparing, we're looking at chimpanzee and bonobo violence

02:50.440 --> 02:54.040
and the difference is between two and three orders

02:54.040 --> 02:57.560
of magnitude, the frequency with which chimps and bonobos

02:57.560 --> 03:00.760
hit each other, chase each other, charge each other,

03:00.760 --> 03:05.760
physically engage is some day between 500 and 1,000 times

03:06.400 --> 03:08.440
higher than in humans.

03:08.440 --> 03:09.960
So there's something just amazing about us

03:09.960 --> 03:13.680
and this has been recognized for centuries.

03:13.680 --> 03:16.040
Aristotle drew attention to the fact

03:16.040 --> 03:19.080
that we behave in many ways like domesticated animals

03:19.080 --> 03:21.360
because we're so unviolent.

03:21.360 --> 03:26.360
But people say, well, what about the hideous engagements

03:26.840 --> 03:31.000
of this 20th century, the First and Second World War

03:31.000 --> 03:33.680
and much else besides.

03:33.680 --> 03:37.160
And that is all proactive violence.

03:37.160 --> 03:42.160
All of that is gangs of people making deliberate decisions

03:43.480 --> 03:46.080
to go off and attack in circumstances

03:46.080 --> 03:49.640
which ideally the attackers are going to be able

03:49.640 --> 03:52.440
to make their kills and then get out of there.

03:53.360 --> 03:55.960
In other words, not face confrontation.

03:55.960 --> 03:58.800
That's the ordinary way that arm is trying to work.

03:58.800 --> 04:03.800
And there it turns out that humans and chimpanzees

04:04.920 --> 04:07.160
are in a very similar kind of state.

04:07.160 --> 04:11.000
That is to say, if you look at the rate of death

04:11.000 --> 04:13.800
from chimpanzees conducting proactive

04:13.840 --> 04:17.200
co-editionary violence, it's very similar

04:17.200 --> 04:20.320
in many ways to what you see in humans.

04:20.320 --> 04:23.600
So when not downregulated with proactive violence,

04:23.600 --> 04:25.760
it's just this reactive violence

04:25.760 --> 04:29.200
that is strikingly reduced in humans.

04:29.200 --> 04:33.240
So chimpanzees also practice kind of tribal warfare.

04:34.080 --> 04:36.080
Indeed they do, yeah.

04:36.080 --> 04:38.960
So this was discovered first in 1974.

04:38.960 --> 04:41.000
It was observed first in 1974,

04:41.960 --> 04:43.640
which was about the time

04:43.640 --> 04:48.640
that the first major study of chimpanzees in the wild

04:49.480 --> 04:54.480
by Jane Goodall had been going for something like five years

04:55.480 --> 05:00.480
during, of the chimpanzees being observed wherever they went.

05:02.760 --> 05:07.000
Until then they'd been observed at a feeding station

05:07.000 --> 05:11.040
where Jane was luring them in to be observed

05:11.040 --> 05:12.920
by seeing bananas, which is great.

05:12.920 --> 05:15.320
She learned a lot, but she didn't learn

05:15.320 --> 05:17.920
what was happening at the edges of their ranges.

05:17.920 --> 05:22.480
So five years later, it became very obvious

05:22.480 --> 05:25.640
that there was hostile relationships between groups.

05:25.640 --> 05:30.560
And those hostile relationships sometimes take the form

05:30.560 --> 05:32.600
of the kind of hostile relationships

05:32.600 --> 05:33.720
that you see in many animals,

05:33.720 --> 05:38.720
which is a bunch of chimps in this case shouting

05:40.360 --> 05:43.920
at a bunch of other chimps on their borders.

05:44.960 --> 05:47.560
But dramatically, in addition to that,

05:47.560 --> 05:49.320
there is a second kind of interaction.

05:49.320 --> 05:54.320
And that is when a party of chimpanzees

05:55.960 --> 05:59.600
makes a deliberate venture

05:59.600 --> 06:02.240
to the edge of their territory,

06:02.240 --> 06:07.240
silently, and then search for members of neighboring groups.

06:08.200 --> 06:11.760
And what they're searching for is a lone individual.

06:11.760 --> 06:13.160
So I've been with chimps

06:13.160 --> 06:17.960
when they've heard a lone individual under these circumstances

06:17.960 --> 06:19.960
or what they think is a lone one

06:19.960 --> 06:23.040
and they touch each other and look at each other

06:23.040 --> 06:26.120
and then charge forward, very excited.

06:27.520 --> 06:30.880
And then while they're charging,

06:30.920 --> 06:35.560
all of a sudden, the place where they heard a lone call

06:35.560 --> 06:37.560
erupts with a volley of calls.

06:37.560 --> 06:40.880
It was just one calling out of a larger party.

06:40.880 --> 06:43.520
And our chimps put on the brakes

06:43.520 --> 06:46.720
and scoot back for safety into their own territory.

06:46.720 --> 06:49.720
But if in fact they do find a lone individual

06:49.720 --> 06:52.480
and they can sneak up to them,

06:52.480 --> 06:55.040
then they make a deliberate attack.

06:55.040 --> 06:57.560
They're hunting, they're stalking and hunting

06:57.560 --> 07:00.680
and then they impose terrible damage,

07:00.680 --> 07:03.080
which typically ends in a kill straight away,

07:03.080 --> 07:08.080
but it might end up with the victim so damaged

07:08.360 --> 07:13.360
that they'll crawl away and die a few days or hours later.

07:13.560 --> 07:15.400
So that was a very dramatic discovery

07:15.400 --> 07:20.400
because it really made people realize for the first time

07:20.520 --> 07:22.800
that Conrad Lorenz had been wrong

07:22.800 --> 07:26.920
when in the 1960s, in his famous book On Aggression,

07:26.920 --> 07:30.800
he said warfare is restricted to humans.

07:30.800 --> 07:33.080
Animals do not deliberately kill each other.

07:33.080 --> 07:35.160
Well, now we know that actually there's a bunch of animals

07:35.160 --> 07:36.400
that deliberately kill each other

07:36.400 --> 07:39.680
and they always do so under essentially the same circumstances

07:39.680 --> 07:44.200
which is when they feel safe doing it.

07:44.200 --> 07:46.880
So humans feel safe doing it when they got a weapon.

07:48.280 --> 07:52.400
Animals feel safe when they have a coalition,

07:52.400 --> 07:54.840
a coalition that has overwhelming power

07:54.840 --> 07:56.720
compared to the victim.

07:56.760 --> 07:59.440
And so wolves will do that and lions will do that

07:59.440 --> 08:00.880
and hyenas will do that

08:00.880 --> 08:04.320
and chimpanzees will do it and humans do it too.

08:05.360 --> 08:08.480
Can they pull themselves into something

08:08.480 --> 08:10.600
that looks more like a symmetric war

08:10.600 --> 08:12.680
as opposed to an asymmetric one?

08:12.680 --> 08:15.320
So accidentally engaging on the lone individual

08:15.320 --> 08:17.240
and getting the cells into trouble?

08:17.240 --> 08:21.400
Are they more aggressive in avoiding these kinds of battles?

08:21.400 --> 08:24.080
No, they're very keen to avoid those kinds of battles,

08:24.120 --> 08:27.720
but occasionally they can make a mistake.

08:28.880 --> 08:32.360
But so far there have been no observations

08:32.360 --> 08:34.760
of anything like a battle in which

08:34.760 --> 08:37.320
both sides maintain themselves.

08:37.320 --> 08:40.320
And I think you can very confidently say

08:40.320 --> 08:42.800
that overwhelmingly what happens is that

08:42.800 --> 08:45.120
if they discover that there's several individuals

08:45.120 --> 08:48.320
on the other side, then both sides retreat.

08:48.320 --> 08:50.360
Nobody wants to get hurt.

08:50.360 --> 08:52.080
What they want to do is to hurt others.

08:52.760 --> 08:56.680
So you mentioned Jane Goodall, you've worked with her.

08:56.680 --> 08:58.160
What was it like working with her?

08:58.160 --> 08:59.760
What have you learned from her?

09:01.120 --> 09:04.960
Well, she's a wonderfully independent, courageous person

09:04.960 --> 09:09.720
who she famously began her studies

09:09.720 --> 09:14.720
not as a qualified person in terms of education,

09:16.320 --> 09:19.640
but qualified only by enthusiasm

09:19.640 --> 09:24.320
and considerable experience even in her early 20s with nature.

09:26.320 --> 09:28.720
So she's courageous in the sense of being able

09:28.720 --> 09:32.080
to take on challenges.

09:32.080 --> 09:34.400
The thing that is very impressive about her

09:34.400 --> 09:39.880
is her total fidelity to the observations,

09:40.920 --> 09:45.920
very unwilling to extend beyond the observations,

09:46.800 --> 09:48.520
waiting until they mount up

09:48.520 --> 09:50.600
and you've really got a confident picture,

09:52.160 --> 09:56.920
and tremendous attention to individuals.

09:56.920 --> 10:00.480
So that was an interesting problem from her point of view

10:00.480 --> 10:05.480
because when she got to know the chimpanzees of Gombe,

10:05.680 --> 10:09.480
this particular community of Casa Calo, about 60 individuals,

10:10.960 --> 10:14.760
so Gombe was in Tanzania on Lake Tanganyika.

10:14.760 --> 10:16.600
She was there initially with her mother

10:16.600 --> 10:20.520
and then alone for two or three years

10:20.520 --> 10:22.760
of really intense observation

10:22.760 --> 10:24.920
and then slowly joined by other people.

10:26.360 --> 10:31.360
What she discovered was that there were obvious differences

10:31.760 --> 10:34.680
in individual personality.

10:34.680 --> 10:39.160
And the difficulty about that was that when she reported this

10:39.160 --> 10:43.160
to the larger scientific world,

10:43.160 --> 10:46.000
initially her advisors at Cambridge,

10:47.560 --> 10:49.960
they said, well, we don't know how to handle that

10:49.960 --> 10:53.200
because you've got to treat all these animals

10:53.200 --> 10:55.040
as the same basically because

10:57.560 --> 11:00.560
there is no research tradition

11:00.560 --> 11:03.320
of thinking about personalities.

11:03.320 --> 11:06.800
Well, now, whatever it is, 60 years later,

11:07.920 --> 11:11.600
the study of personalities is a very rich part

11:11.600 --> 11:13.320
of the study of animal behavior.

11:14.720 --> 11:18.040
At any rate, the important point in terms of what was she like

11:18.040 --> 11:20.360
is that she stuck to her guns and she absolutely insisted

11:20.360 --> 11:25.360
that we have to show, describe in great detail,

11:25.360 --> 11:28.440
the differences in personality among these individuals

11:28.440 --> 11:30.480
and then you can leave it to the evolutionary biologist

11:30.480 --> 11:32.720
to think about what it means.

11:32.720 --> 11:37.720
So what is the process of observation like this like?

11:37.960 --> 11:39.280
Observing the personality,

11:39.280 --> 11:43.920
but also observing in a way that's not projecting your beliefs

11:43.920 --> 11:48.840
about human nature or animal nature onto chimps,

11:48.840 --> 11:52.600
which is probably really tempting to project.

11:52.600 --> 11:55.960
So your understanding of the way the human world works,

11:55.960 --> 11:59.440
projecting that onto the chimp world.

11:59.440 --> 12:01.640
Yes, I mean, it's particularly difficult with chimps

12:01.640 --> 12:05.240
because chimps are so similar to humans in their behavior

12:05.240 --> 12:09.000
that it's very easy to make those projections.

12:09.000 --> 12:12.240
As you say, the process involves

12:13.440 --> 12:17.000
making very clear definitions of what a behavior is.

12:18.520 --> 12:23.520
Aggression can be defined in terms of a forceful hit,

12:24.320 --> 12:25.680
a bite and so on.

12:26.800 --> 12:30.360
And writing down every time these things happen

12:30.360 --> 12:32.720
and then slowly totting up the numbers of times

12:32.720 --> 12:36.680
that they happen from individual A towards individuals,

12:36.680 --> 12:41.640
B, C, D and E, so that you build up a very concrete picture

12:41.640 --> 12:43.800
rather than interpreting at any point

12:43.800 --> 12:45.640
and stopping and saying, well,

12:45.640 --> 12:47.400
they seem to be rather aggressive.

12:48.440 --> 12:53.360
So the formal system is that you build up a pattern

12:53.360 --> 12:57.440
of the relationships based on a description

12:57.440 --> 12:59.520
of the different types of interactions,

12:59.520 --> 13:02.040
the aggressive and the friendly interactions.

13:03.040 --> 13:06.040
And all of these are defined in concrete.

13:07.600 --> 13:12.280
And so from that, you extract a pattern of relationships.

13:12.280 --> 13:16.280
And the relationships can be defined as

13:18.600 --> 13:23.760
relatively friendly, relatively aggressive, competitive,

13:23.760 --> 13:27.440
based on the frequency of these types of interactions.

13:27.440 --> 13:31.000
And so one can talk in terms of individuals

13:31.040 --> 13:35.040
having a relationship which on the scores of friendliness

13:35.040 --> 13:38.160
is two standard deviations outside the mean.

13:39.360 --> 13:41.040
I mean, you know, it's-

13:41.040 --> 13:44.680
In which direction, sorry, both directions?

13:45.720 --> 13:48.920
Well, I mean, there will be obviously the friendly ones

13:48.920 --> 13:52.040
would be the ones who have exceptionally high rates

13:52.040 --> 13:54.480
of spending time close to each other,

13:54.480 --> 13:56.600
of touching each other in a gentle way,

13:56.600 --> 13:59.120
of grooming each other.

13:59.120 --> 14:01.120
And by the way, finding that those things

14:01.120 --> 14:03.440
are correlated with each other.

14:03.440 --> 14:08.360
So it's possible to define a friendship with a capital F

14:08.360 --> 14:10.160
in a very systematic way.

14:10.160 --> 14:14.800
And to compare that between individuals,

14:14.800 --> 14:18.800
but also between communities of chimpanzees

14:18.800 --> 14:21.120
and between different species.

14:21.120 --> 14:23.480
So that, you know, we can say that in some species,

14:23.480 --> 14:26.880
individuals have friends and others, they don't at all.

14:26.880 --> 14:29.720
What about just because there's different personalities

14:29.720 --> 14:31.920
and because they're so fascinating,

14:31.920 --> 14:33.640
what about sort of falling in love

14:33.640 --> 14:37.240
or forming friendships with chimps, you know?

14:37.240 --> 14:42.240
Like really, you know, connecting with them as an observer.

14:43.920 --> 14:46.360
What role does that play?

14:46.360 --> 14:48.000
Is you're tracking these individuals

14:48.000 --> 14:50.800
that are full of life and intelligence

14:50.800 --> 14:55.640
for long periods of time, plus as a human,

14:55.680 --> 14:58.160
especially in those days for Jane,

14:58.160 --> 15:00.320
she's alone observing it.

15:00.320 --> 15:02.120
It gets lonely as a human.

15:02.120 --> 15:04.800
I mean, probably deeply lonely as a human

15:04.800 --> 15:07.760
being observed these other intelligent species.

15:07.760 --> 15:08.920
It's a very reasonable question.

15:08.920 --> 15:11.640
And of course, Jane in those early years,

15:11.640 --> 15:15.320
I think she's willing now to talk about the fact

15:15.320 --> 15:19.880
that she regrets to some extent how close she became.

15:21.480 --> 15:23.680
And the problem is not just from the humans,

15:23.680 --> 15:25.480
the problem is from the chimpanzees as well,

15:25.480 --> 15:30.320
because they do things that are extremely affectionate,

15:31.640 --> 15:35.040
if you like, you know, at one point,

15:35.040 --> 15:40.040
Jane offered a ripe fruit to a chimpanzee

15:40.720 --> 15:42.280
called David Greybeard.

15:42.280 --> 15:46.400
David Greybeard took it and squeezed her hand

15:47.720 --> 15:48.840
as if to say thank you.

15:48.840 --> 15:51.200
And then I think he gave it back if I remember rightly.

15:51.200 --> 15:52.040
Yeah.

15:53.520 --> 15:55.080
No, thank you.

15:55.080 --> 15:55.920
All right.

15:57.400 --> 15:59.440
Oh, it's almost like thank you

15:59.440 --> 16:02.920
and returning the affection by giving the fruit

16:02.920 --> 16:04.240
if they did something like that.

16:04.240 --> 16:06.080
You know, it was a gentle squeeze.

16:06.080 --> 16:08.200
I mean, chimpanzees could squeeze you very hard

16:08.200 --> 16:10.280
as that occasionally has happened.

16:11.440 --> 16:13.520
Some chimps are aggressive to people

16:14.720 --> 16:16.480
and others are friendly.

16:16.480 --> 16:19.000
And the ones that are friendly tend to be

16:19.000 --> 16:20.320
rather sympathetic characters

16:20.320 --> 16:24.240
because they might be ones who are having problems

16:24.280 --> 16:26.440
in their own society.

16:26.440 --> 16:30.160
So Joe Mio in Gombe used to come and sit next to me

16:30.160 --> 16:33.840
quite often and he was having a hard time

16:33.840 --> 16:35.840
making it in that society,

16:35.840 --> 16:36.880
which I can describe to you

16:36.880 --> 16:39.760
in terms of the number of aggressive interactions if you want,

16:39.760 --> 16:43.360
but just to be informed about it.

16:43.360 --> 16:48.360
So all of this is a temptation to be very firmly resisted.

16:49.200 --> 16:51.720
And in the community that I've been working with

16:51.720 --> 16:53.360
in Uganda for the last 30 years,

16:53.400 --> 16:56.120
we try extremely hard to impress

16:56.120 --> 16:58.440
on all of the research students who come with us

16:58.440 --> 17:00.160
that it is absolutely vital

17:00.160 --> 17:02.800
that you do not fall into that temptation.

17:02.800 --> 17:05.920
Now, you know, we heard a story of one person

17:05.920 --> 17:09.360
who did reach out and touch one of our chimps.

17:09.360 --> 17:12.240
It's a very, very bad idea.

17:12.240 --> 17:16.400
Not because the chimp is going to do anything violent

17:16.400 --> 17:21.200
at the time, but because if they learn

17:21.200 --> 17:24.440
that humans are as weak physically

17:24.440 --> 17:26.080
as we are compared to them,

17:26.080 --> 17:28.800
then they can take advantage of it, us.

17:28.800 --> 17:30.800
And that's what happened in Gombe.

17:30.800 --> 17:35.400
So after Jane had done the very obvious thing

17:35.400 --> 17:38.840
when you're first engaged in this game

17:38.840 --> 17:41.600
of allowing the infants to approach her

17:41.600 --> 17:43.840
and then tickling them and playing with them,

17:45.560 --> 17:49.200
some of those infants had the personality

17:49.200 --> 17:53.360
of wanting to take advantage of that knowledge later.

17:53.360 --> 17:56.120
And so, you know, you had an individual, Frodo,

17:56.120 --> 17:59.280
who was violent on a regular basis

17:59.280 --> 18:00.760
towards humans when he was an adult

18:00.760 --> 18:01.720
and he was quite dangerous.

18:01.720 --> 18:02.960
I mean, he could easily have killed someone.

18:02.960 --> 18:05.120
In fact, he did kill one person.

18:05.120 --> 18:09.760
He killed a baby that he took from a mother,

18:09.760 --> 18:12.040
a human baby that he took off her hip

18:12.040 --> 18:13.880
when he met her on the path.

18:14.840 --> 18:18.720
So, you know, it's a reminder that we're dealing with

18:18.720 --> 18:22.080
a species that are rather human-like

18:22.080 --> 18:24.040
in the range of emotions they have,

18:24.040 --> 18:25.960
in the capacities they have,

18:25.960 --> 18:28.560
and even in the strength they have,

18:28.560 --> 18:32.720
they are, you know, in many ways stronger than humans.

18:32.720 --> 18:34.840
So it's a...

18:34.840 --> 18:36.800
You've got to be careful.

18:36.800 --> 18:39.600
So in the full range of friendliness and violence,

18:39.600 --> 18:43.480
the capacity for these very human things.

18:44.120 --> 18:47.360
Yes, I mean, it's very obvious with violence,

18:47.360 --> 18:50.280
as we talked about, you know, that they will kill,

18:50.280 --> 18:52.120
they will kill not just strangers.

18:53.320 --> 18:57.680
They can kill other adults within their own group.

18:57.680 --> 18:59.720
They can kill babies that are strangers.

18:59.720 --> 19:01.280
They can kill babies in their own group.

19:01.280 --> 19:04.480
So, you know, this is a long-lived individual.

19:04.480 --> 19:06.720
Obviously, these killings can't have very often

19:06.720 --> 19:09.400
because otherwise they'd all be dead.

19:09.400 --> 19:13.440
And we're now finding that they can live to 50 or 60 years

19:13.440 --> 19:16.240
in the wild at relatively low population density

19:16.240 --> 19:17.360
because they're big animals,

19:17.360 --> 19:20.520
eating a rather specialized kind of food, the ripe fruits.

19:22.440 --> 19:23.960
So it doesn't happen all the time.

19:23.960 --> 19:28.840
With friendliness, they are very strong to support each other.

19:28.840 --> 19:33.840
They very much depend on their close friendships,

19:34.680 --> 19:38.960
which they express through physical contact.

19:39.000 --> 19:41.680
And particularly through grooming.

19:41.680 --> 19:45.760
So grooming occurs when one individual approaches another

19:45.760 --> 19:48.320
and might present for grooming,

19:48.320 --> 19:52.120
a very common way of starting, turning their back

19:52.120 --> 19:53.880
or presenting an arm or something like that.

19:53.880 --> 19:57.880
And the other just riffles their fingers through the hair.

19:57.880 --> 20:00.520
And that's partly just soothing.

20:00.520 --> 20:04.400
And it's partly looking for parasites,

20:04.400 --> 20:05.800
but mostly it's just soothing.

20:05.800 --> 20:06.640
Yes.

20:07.280 --> 20:12.080
The point about this is it can go on for half an hour.

20:12.080 --> 20:15.480
It can go on for sometimes even an hour.

20:15.480 --> 20:20.080
So this is a major expression of interest in somebody else.

20:21.360 --> 20:25.760
When did your interest in this one particular aspect

20:25.760 --> 20:29.000
of chimp come to be, which is violence?

20:29.000 --> 20:32.320
When did the study of violence in chimps

20:32.320 --> 20:34.520
become something you're deeply interested in?

20:35.520 --> 20:40.520
Well, for my PhD in the early 1970s,

20:41.520 --> 20:43.040
I was in Gombe with Jane Goodall

20:43.040 --> 20:46.200
and was studying feeding behavior.

20:46.200 --> 20:49.080
But during that time, we were seeing,

20:49.080 --> 20:52.440
and I say we because there were half a dozen

20:52.440 --> 20:55.840
research students all in her camp,

20:58.440 --> 21:02.360
we were discovering that chimps had this capacity

21:02.400 --> 21:05.080
for violence.

21:05.080 --> 21:07.520
The first kill happened during that time,

21:07.520 --> 21:10.040
which was of an infant and a neighboring group.

21:11.720 --> 21:15.280
And we were starting to see these hunting expeditions.

21:16.160 --> 21:18.880
And this was the start of my interest

21:18.880 --> 21:21.840
because it was such chilling evidence

21:21.840 --> 21:26.840
of an extraordinary similarity between chimps and humans.

21:27.840 --> 21:31.800
Now, at that time, we didn't know very much

21:31.800 --> 21:35.560
about how chimpanzees and humans were related.

21:35.560 --> 21:41.040
Chimps, gorillas, bonobos are all three big black hairy things

21:41.040 --> 21:45.040
that live in the African forests and eat fruits

21:45.040 --> 21:49.760
and leaves when they can't find fruits and walk on their knuckles.

21:49.760 --> 21:51.320
And they all look rather similar to each other.

21:51.320 --> 21:54.320
So they seem as though those three species,

21:54.840 --> 21:56.720
chimps and gorillas and bonobos,

21:56.720 --> 21:59.400
should all be each other's closest relatives.

21:59.400 --> 22:01.520
And humans are something rather separate.

22:01.520 --> 22:04.640
And so any of them would be of interest to us.

22:04.640 --> 22:08.520
Subsequently, we learn that actually that's not true

22:08.520 --> 22:10.440
and that there's a special relationship

22:10.440 --> 22:13.400
between humans and chimpanzees.

22:13.400 --> 22:15.920
But at the time, even without knowing that,

22:15.920 --> 22:18.440
it was obvious that there was something very odd

22:18.440 --> 22:22.760
about chimpanzees because Jane had discovered

22:22.840 --> 22:25.440
they were making tools.

22:25.440 --> 22:29.080
She had seen that they were hunting meat.

22:29.080 --> 22:33.200
She had seen that they were sharing the meat among each other.

22:33.200 --> 22:35.200
She had seen that the societies

22:35.200 --> 22:37.320
were dominated politically by males,

22:37.320 --> 22:38.680
coalitions of males.

22:38.680 --> 22:40.480
All of these things, of course, resonate

22:40.480 --> 22:43.200
so closely with humans.

22:43.200 --> 22:47.440
And then it turns out that in contrast

22:47.440 --> 22:50.120
to conventional wisdom at the time,

22:50.120 --> 22:53.240
the chimpanzees were capable of hunting

22:53.240 --> 22:55.320
and killing members of neighboring groups.

22:56.680 --> 23:00.440
Well, at that point, the similarities

23:00.440 --> 23:04.640
between chimps and humans become less a matter

23:04.640 --> 23:09.200
of sort of sheer intellectual fascination

23:09.200 --> 23:11.560
than something that has a really deep meaning

23:11.560 --> 23:14.600
about our understanding of ourselves.

23:15.640 --> 23:19.760
I mean, until then, you can cheerfully think of humans

23:19.760 --> 23:22.960
as a species apart from the rest of nature

23:22.960 --> 23:24.800
because we are so peculiar.

23:24.800 --> 23:28.480
But when it turns out that, as it turns out,

23:28.480 --> 23:30.000
one of our two closest relatives

23:31.800 --> 23:34.840
has got these features that we share

23:34.840 --> 23:37.720
and that one of the features is something

23:37.720 --> 23:42.640
that is the most horrendous, as well as fascinating,

23:42.640 --> 23:46.440
aspect of human behavior, then how can you resist

23:46.440 --> 23:49.320
just trying to find out what's going on?

23:50.000 --> 23:51.640
So I have to say this.

23:51.640 --> 23:54.480
I'm not sure if you're familiar with the man,

23:54.480 --> 23:56.360
but fans of this podcast are.

23:56.360 --> 23:59.960
So we're talking about chimps, we're talking about violence.

23:59.960 --> 24:04.320
My now friend, Mr. Joe Rogan, is a big fan of those things.

24:04.320 --> 24:06.160
I'm a big fan of these topics.

24:06.160 --> 24:10.160
I think a lot of people are fascinated by these topics.

24:10.160 --> 24:15.160
So as you're saying, why do we find the exploration

24:16.640 --> 24:19.600
of violence and the relations between chimps

24:19.600 --> 24:20.920
so interesting?

24:20.920 --> 24:24.000
What can they teach us about ourselves?

24:26.200 --> 24:29.800
Until we had this information about chimpanzees,

24:29.800 --> 24:34.800
it was possible to believe that the psychology

24:37.560 --> 24:42.560
behind warfare was totally the result

24:43.640 --> 24:48.640
of some kind of cultural, recent cultural innovation.

24:49.600 --> 24:51.600
It had nothing to do with our biology.

24:52.600 --> 24:56.240
Or if you like, that it's got something to do with sin

24:56.240 --> 24:59.480
and God and the devil and that sort of thing.

25:01.000 --> 25:06.000
But what the chimps tell us after we think carefully about it

25:08.200 --> 25:11.720
is that it seems undoubtedly the case

25:11.720 --> 25:16.720
that our evolutionary psychology has given us

25:17.720 --> 25:22.720
the same kind of attitude towards violence

25:22.720 --> 25:25.440
as occurred in chimpanzees.

25:26.480 --> 25:29.400
And in both species, it has evolved

25:29.400 --> 25:32.120
because of its evolutionary significance.

25:32.120 --> 25:34.640
In other words, because it's been helpful

25:34.640 --> 25:37.920
to the individuals who have practiced it.

25:37.920 --> 25:41.920
And now we know that, as I mentioned,

25:41.920 --> 25:44.160
other species do this as well.

25:44.160 --> 25:49.160
In fact, wolves, which this is a really

25:49.240 --> 25:54.240
kind of ironical observation, Conrad Lorenz,

25:54.240 --> 25:56.440
who I mentioned had been the person who thought

25:56.440 --> 26:00.720
that human aggression in the form of killing

26:00.720 --> 26:04.120
members of our own species was unique to our species.

26:04.120 --> 26:05.640
He was a great fan of wolves.

26:05.640 --> 26:07.040
He studied wolves.

26:07.040 --> 26:11.040
And in captivity, he noted that wolves are very unlikely

26:11.040 --> 26:15.840
to harm each other in spats among members

26:15.840 --> 26:17.480
of the same group.

26:17.480 --> 26:19.200
What happens is that one of them will roll over

26:19.200 --> 26:20.680
and present their neck, much as you see

26:20.680 --> 26:22.440
in a dog park nowadays.

26:22.440 --> 26:25.720
And the other might put their jaws on the neck

26:25.720 --> 26:26.640
but will not bite.

26:27.840 --> 26:30.320
Okay, so now it turns out that if you study wolves

26:30.320 --> 26:34.080
in the wild, then neighboring packs

26:34.080 --> 26:36.800
often go hunting for each other.

26:36.800 --> 26:39.360
They are in fierce competition.

26:39.360 --> 26:43.760
And as much as 50% of the mortality of wolves

26:43.760 --> 26:47.600
is due to being killed by other wolves, adult mortality.

26:47.600 --> 26:48.440
Wow.

26:48.440 --> 26:50.280
So it's a really serious business.

26:51.360 --> 26:55.540
The chimpanzees and humans fit into a larger pattern

26:55.540 --> 26:57.920
of understanding animals in which

26:59.800 --> 27:02.080
you don't have an instinct for violence.

27:02.080 --> 27:05.160
What you have is an instinct, if you like,

27:05.160 --> 27:07.840
to use violence adaptively.

27:07.880 --> 27:11.760
And if the right circumstances come up, it'll be adaptive.

27:11.760 --> 27:14.800
If the right circumstances don't come up, it won't be.

27:14.800 --> 27:18.440
So some chimpanzee communities are much more violent

27:18.440 --> 27:22.240
than others because of things like the frequency

27:22.240 --> 27:25.880
with which a large party of males is likely

27:25.880 --> 27:28.120
to meet a lone victim.

27:28.120 --> 27:30.560
And that's going to depend on the local ecology.

27:31.960 --> 27:35.760
But so the overall answer to the question

27:35.840 --> 27:39.360
what a chimps teach us is that we have to take

27:39.360 --> 27:43.360
very seriously the notion that in humans,

27:44.280 --> 27:49.040
the tendency to make war is a consequence

27:49.040 --> 27:52.440
of a long-term evolutionary adaptation

27:52.440 --> 27:55.120
and not just a military ideology

27:55.120 --> 27:59.360
or some sort of local patriarchal phenomenon.

28:00.440 --> 28:03.080
And of course, a reading of history,

28:03.080 --> 28:07.200
a judicious reading of history fits that very easily

28:07.200 --> 28:09.920
because war is so commonplace.

28:10.880 --> 28:11.800
It's not an accident.

28:11.800 --> 28:14.640
So it's not a construction of human civilization.

28:14.640 --> 28:17.600
It's deeply within us, violence.

28:17.600 --> 28:20.480
So what's the difference between violence

28:20.480 --> 28:23.000
on the individual level versus group?

28:24.720 --> 28:26.960
It seems like with chimps and with wolves,

28:26.960 --> 28:30.840
there's something about the dynamic of multiple

28:31.840 --> 28:36.320
chimps together that increase the chance of violence.

28:36.320 --> 28:41.040
Or is violence still fundamentally part of the individual?

28:41.040 --> 28:45.040
Like would an individual be as violent

28:45.040 --> 28:48.000
as they might be as part of a group?

28:48.000 --> 28:51.240
If we're talking about killing,

28:51.240 --> 28:54.240
then violence in the sense of killing

28:54.240 --> 28:59.000
is very much associated with a group.

28:59.040 --> 29:03.960
And the reason is that individuals don't benefit

29:03.960 --> 29:05.600
by getting into a fight

29:05.600 --> 29:08.680
in which they risk being hurt themselves.

29:08.680 --> 29:12.680
So it's only when you have overwhelming power

29:12.680 --> 29:16.800
that the temptation to try and kill another victim

29:16.800 --> 29:20.640
rises sufficiently for them to be motivated to do it.

29:23.400 --> 29:27.880
The average number of chimpanzee males

29:27.920 --> 29:30.520
that attack a single male

29:30.520 --> 29:33.200
in something like 50 observations

29:33.200 --> 29:36.040
that have accumulated in the last 50 years

29:36.040 --> 29:41.040
from various different study sites is eight, eight to one.

29:41.960 --> 29:46.840
Now sometimes it can go as low as three to one,

29:46.840 --> 29:49.520
but that's getting risky.

29:49.520 --> 29:51.680
But if you have eight, you can see what can happen.

29:51.680 --> 29:55.960
I mean, basically you have one male on one foot,

29:55.960 --> 29:57.120
another male on another foot,

29:57.120 --> 29:59.680
another male on an arm, another male on another arm.

29:59.680 --> 30:02.520
Now you have an immobilized victim

30:02.520 --> 30:06.360
with four individuals capable of just doing the damage.

30:06.360 --> 30:08.720
And so they can then move in and tear out his thorax

30:08.720 --> 30:10.200
and tear off his testicles

30:10.200 --> 30:12.560
and twist an arm until it breaks

30:12.560 --> 30:16.760
and do this, you know, appalling damage with no weapons.

30:18.480 --> 30:23.480
What is the way in which they prefer to commit the violence?

30:23.680 --> 30:24.880
Is there something to be said

30:24.880 --> 30:27.840
about like the actual process of it?

30:27.840 --> 30:29.400
Is there an artistry to it?

30:29.400 --> 30:32.400
So if you look at human warfare,

30:32.400 --> 30:34.240
there's different parts in history,

30:34.240 --> 30:37.840
preferred different kind of approaches to violence.

30:37.840 --> 30:41.280
It had more to do with tools, I think, on the human side.

30:41.280 --> 30:44.880
But just the nature of violence itself,

30:44.880 --> 30:47.560
sorry, the practice, the strategy of violence,

30:47.560 --> 30:49.120
is it basically the same?

30:49.120 --> 30:53.440
You improvise, you immobilize the victim

30:53.440 --> 30:55.000
and they just rip off different parts

30:55.000 --> 30:56.800
of their body kind of thing.

30:56.800 --> 30:59.880
Yeah, you have to understand that these things

30:59.880 --> 31:04.880
are happening at high speed in thick vegetation, mostly.

31:06.160 --> 31:09.800
So they have not been filmed carefully.

31:09.800 --> 31:13.720
You know, we have a few little glimpses of them

31:13.720 --> 31:16.440
from one or two people like David Watts,

31:16.440 --> 31:17.960
who's got some great video,

31:17.960 --> 31:21.360
but we don't know enough to be able to say that.

31:21.360 --> 31:23.920
It's hard for me to imagine that there are styles

31:23.920 --> 31:28.480
that vary between communities, you know, cultural styles,

31:28.480 --> 31:32.880
but it is possible and one thing that is striking

31:32.880 --> 31:35.920
is that the number of times

31:35.920 --> 31:39.280
that an individual victim has been killed immediately

31:40.240 --> 31:45.240
has been higher in Kibali Forest in Uganda

31:45.240 --> 31:48.640
than in Gombe National Park in Tanzania.

31:48.640 --> 31:50.200
It's conceivable, that's just chance.

31:50.200 --> 31:54.360
We don't have real numbers now, but what is this?

31:54.360 --> 31:55.440
I can't remember exact numbers,

31:55.440 --> 31:58.240
but you know, 10 versus 15 or something.

32:00.160 --> 32:05.160
So maybe they damage to the point of expecting a death

32:06.480 --> 32:09.160
in one place and they just finish it off in the other,

32:09.160 --> 32:12.120
but most likely that sort of difference

32:12.120 --> 32:17.120
will be due to differences in the numbers of attackers.

32:17.200 --> 32:19.920
You know, human beings are able to conceive

32:19.920 --> 32:23.400
of the philosophical notion of death, of mortality.

32:23.400 --> 32:27.520
Is there any of that for chimps

32:28.560 --> 32:30.520
when they're thinking about violence?

32:30.520 --> 32:33.560
Is violence, like what is the nature

32:33.560 --> 32:36.560
of their conception of violence, do you think?

32:36.560 --> 32:41.640
Do they realize they're taking another conscious being's life,

32:41.640 --> 32:45.960
or is it some kind of like optimization

32:45.960 --> 32:48.560
over the use of resources or something like that?

32:50.440 --> 32:53.840
I don't think it's, I can't think of any way to get it

32:53.840 --> 32:56.760
in answer to the question of what they know about that.

32:58.120 --> 33:03.120
I think that the way to think about the motivation

33:03.320 --> 33:08.320
is rather like the motivation in sex.

33:09.880 --> 33:14.640
So when males are interested in having sex with a female,

33:14.640 --> 33:17.080
whether it's in chimpanzees or in humans,

33:18.880 --> 33:22.040
they don't think about the fact that what this is going to do

33:22.040 --> 33:23.320
is to lead to a baby.

33:24.160 --> 33:25.280
Mostly.

33:25.280 --> 33:26.120
You're right.

33:26.120 --> 33:27.600
Mostly what they're thinking about is,

33:27.600 --> 33:28.960
I want to get my end away.

33:29.920 --> 33:34.520
And I think that it's a similar kind of process

33:34.520 --> 33:35.800
with the chimps.

33:35.800 --> 33:37.720
What they are thinking about is,

33:38.720 --> 33:41.720
I want to kill this individual.

33:41.760 --> 33:43.560
And it's hard to imagine that

33:45.200 --> 33:47.640
taking the other individual's perspective

33:47.640 --> 33:50.240
and thinking about what it means for them to die

33:50.240 --> 33:51.800
is going to be an important part of that.

33:51.800 --> 33:53.800
In fact, there's reasons to think

33:53.800 --> 33:55.160
it should not be an important part of it

33:55.160 --> 33:56.120
because it might inhibit them.

33:56.120 --> 33:58.000
And they don't want to be inhibited.

33:58.000 --> 34:01.720
They're more efficient they are in doing this the better.

34:01.720 --> 34:03.640
But I think it's interesting to think about this

34:03.640 --> 34:04.760
whole motivational question

34:04.760 --> 34:09.760
because it does produce the sort of rather haunting thought

34:09.840 --> 34:11.800
that there has been selection

34:11.800 --> 34:15.640
in favor of enthusiasm about killing.

34:17.080 --> 34:22.080
And in our relatively gentle

34:22.080 --> 34:26.640
and deliberately moral society that we have today,

34:26.640 --> 34:29.080
it's very difficult for us to face the thought

34:29.080 --> 34:32.560
that in all of us,

34:32.560 --> 34:37.320
there might have been a residue

34:37.320 --> 34:38.800
and more than that,

34:38.800 --> 34:43.640
sort of an active potential for that thought

34:43.640 --> 34:46.640
of really enjoying killing someone else.

34:47.680 --> 34:52.680
But I think one can sustain that thought fairly obviously

34:52.680 --> 34:56.960
by thinking of circumstances in which it would be true

34:58.000 --> 35:03.000
that the ordinary human male would be delighted

35:03.640 --> 35:06.680
to be part of a group that was killing someone.

35:06.680 --> 35:10.440
What you've got to do is to be in a position

35:10.440 --> 35:14.320
where you're regarding the victim as dangerous

35:14.320 --> 35:16.440
and thoroughly hostile.

35:17.640 --> 35:21.080
But the pure enjoyment of violence.

35:21.080 --> 35:23.960
There's, I don't know if you know this historian,

35:23.960 --> 35:26.040
Dan Carlin, he has a podcast.

35:26.040 --> 35:31.040
He has an episode three, four hour episode

35:32.120 --> 35:34.960
that I recommend to others, it's quite haunting.

35:34.960 --> 35:38.400
But he takes us through an entire history.

35:38.400 --> 35:40.800
It's called painful tainment.

35:40.800 --> 35:45.800
The history of humans enjoying the murder of others

35:47.720 --> 35:48.920
in a large group.

35:48.920 --> 35:51.840
So like public executions were part of,

35:51.840 --> 35:53.640
long part of human history.

35:53.640 --> 35:58.280
And there's something that for some reason,

35:58.280 --> 36:03.400
humans seem to have been drawn to just watching others die.

36:03.400 --> 36:06.840
And he ventures to say that that may still be part of us.

36:06.840 --> 36:11.440
For example, he said if it was possible to televise,

36:11.440 --> 36:14.480
to stream online, for example, the execution

36:14.480 --> 36:18.040
and the murder of somebody or even the torture of somebody

36:18.040 --> 36:23.040
that a very large fraction of the population on earth

36:23.280 --> 36:25.040
would not be able to look away.

36:25.040 --> 36:26.800
They'd be drawn to that somehow.

36:26.800 --> 36:31.800
As a very dark thought that we were drawn to that.

36:31.800 --> 36:34.080
So you think that's part of us in there somewhere,

36:34.080 --> 36:39.080
that selection that we evolved for the enjoyment of killing

36:39.400 --> 36:44.400
and the enjoyment of observing those in our tribe

36:46.440 --> 36:47.520
doing the killing.

36:48.400 --> 36:51.240
Yes, I mean, and that word you produced at the end

36:51.240 --> 36:56.240
is critical, I think, because it would be a little bit weird,

36:56.360 --> 37:00.840
I think, to imagine a lot of enjoyment

37:00.840 --> 37:03.760
about people in your own tribe being killed.

37:03.760 --> 37:04.600
Right.

37:04.600 --> 37:06.320
I don't think we're interested in violence

37:06.320 --> 37:08.440
for violence's sake that much.

37:09.920 --> 37:14.920
It's when you get these social boundaries set up.

37:15.440 --> 37:19.480
And in today's world, happily,

37:20.880 --> 37:24.080
we kind of are already one world.

37:25.720 --> 37:29.240
You have to dehumanise someone to get to the point

37:29.240 --> 37:34.240
where they are really outside our recognition of a tribe

37:34.240 --> 37:37.400
at some level, which is the whole human species.

37:37.400 --> 37:41.160
But in ancient times, that would not have been true,

37:41.160 --> 37:42.680
because in ancient times,

37:43.920 --> 37:47.320
there are lots of accounts of hunters and gatherers

37:47.320 --> 37:50.440
in which the appearance of a stranger

37:51.960 --> 37:56.960
would lead to an immediate response of shooting on site.

37:57.440 --> 38:00.640
Because what was human was the people

38:00.640 --> 38:03.280
that were in your society.

38:03.280 --> 38:06.160
And the other things that actually looked like us,

38:06.160 --> 38:09.760
and were human in that sense, were not regarded as human.

38:10.760 --> 38:13.680
So there was a kind of automatic dehumanisation

38:13.680 --> 38:16.200
of everybody that didn't speak our language

38:16.200 --> 38:20.680
or hadn't already somehow become recognised

38:20.680 --> 38:25.680
as sufficiently like us to escape the dehumanisation

38:27.040 --> 38:27.880
of the human population.

38:27.880 --> 38:30.000
And so hopefully the story of human history

38:30.000 --> 38:35.000
is that we are, that tribalism fades away,

38:35.280 --> 38:39.160
that our dehumanisation, the natural desire to dehumanise,

38:39.160 --> 38:42.320
or tendency to dehumanise groups

38:42.320 --> 38:45.840
that are not within this tribe decreases over time.

38:45.840 --> 38:49.800
And so then the desire for violence decreases over time.

38:49.800 --> 38:52.560
Yeah, I mean, that's the optimistic perspective.

38:52.560 --> 38:56.280
And the great sort of concern, of course,

38:56.280 --> 39:00.440
is that small conflicts can build up into bigger conflicts

39:00.440 --> 39:02.160
and then dehumanisation happens

39:02.160 --> 39:03.720
and then violence is released.

39:04.840 --> 39:09.600
As Hannah Arendt says, there currently is no known alternative

39:09.600 --> 39:14.400
to war as a means of settling really important conflicts.

39:16.560 --> 39:18.800
So if we look at the big picture,

39:18.800 --> 39:22.040
what role has violence or do you think violence

39:22.040 --> 39:25.040
has played in the evolution of homo sapiens?

39:25.040 --> 39:29.680
So we are quite an intelligent, got a beautiful,

39:29.680 --> 39:32.960
particular little branch on the evolutionary tree.

39:34.080 --> 39:39.080
What part of that was played by our tendency to be violent?

39:41.840 --> 39:43.960
Well, I think that violence was responsible

39:43.960 --> 39:46.240
for creating your homo sapiens.

39:49.360 --> 39:54.360
And that raises the question of what homo sapiens is.

39:55.040 --> 39:55.880
Yes.

39:57.240 --> 39:58.720
Yeah, exactly.

39:58.720 --> 40:03.720
So nowadays people begin the sort of concept

40:06.640 --> 40:10.800
of what homo sapiens is by thinking about features

40:10.800 --> 40:12.360
that are very obviously different

40:12.360 --> 40:14.800
from all of the other species of homo.

40:15.680 --> 40:20.680
And our large brain, our very rounded cranium,

40:21.160 --> 40:24.240
our relatively small face, these are characteristics

40:24.240 --> 40:27.720
which are developed in a relatively modern way

40:27.720 --> 40:31.160
by about 170,000 years ago.

40:31.160 --> 40:33.960
Say, it's one of the earliest skulls in Africa

40:33.960 --> 40:36.560
that really captures that.

40:36.560 --> 40:41.560
But it has been argued that that is an episode

40:44.280 --> 40:49.280
in a process that has been started substantially earlier.

40:50.280 --> 40:52.240
And there's no doubt that that's true.

40:52.320 --> 40:55.200
Homo sapiens is a species that has been changing

40:55.200 --> 41:00.200
pretty continuously throughout the length of time it's there.

41:00.360 --> 41:03.480
And it goes back to 300,000 years ago.

41:03.480 --> 41:08.480
315, naturally, is the time, the best estimate of a date

41:08.680 --> 41:13.680
for a series of bones from Morocco that have been dated

41:14.880 --> 41:16.960
three or four years ago at that time

41:16.960 --> 41:21.480
and have been characterized as earliest homo sapiens.

41:21.480 --> 41:25.680
Now, at that point, they are only beginning

41:25.680 --> 41:27.840
the trend of sapienization.

41:27.840 --> 41:31.840
And that trend consists basically of grassinization,

41:31.840 --> 41:36.840
of making our ancestors less robust, shorter faces,

41:37.920 --> 41:40.720
smaller teeth, smaller brow ridge,

41:40.720 --> 41:45.520
narrower face, thinner cranium,

41:45.520 --> 41:48.440
all these things that are associated

41:48.440 --> 41:50.960
with reduced violence.

41:51.880 --> 41:56.200
Okay, so that's saying, well, that's homo sapiens beginning.

41:56.200 --> 41:59.640
So it began sometime three to 400,000 years ago

41:59.640 --> 42:01.640
because by 315,000 years ago,

42:01.640 --> 42:03.400
you've already got something recognizable.

42:03.400 --> 42:05.200
So you're more on that side of things

42:05.200 --> 42:06.760
that those are this gradual process.

42:06.760 --> 42:09.240
It's not 150, 170,000 years ago.

42:09.240 --> 42:13.600
It started like 400,000 years ago.

42:13.600 --> 42:14.440
And it's just-

42:14.440 --> 42:16.400
It started three to 400,000 years ago.

42:16.400 --> 42:19.960
And if you look at 170, it's got even more like us.

42:19.960 --> 42:23.600
And then if you look at 100, it's got more like us again.

42:23.600 --> 42:25.440
And if you look at 50, it's more like us again.

42:25.440 --> 42:26.360
It's all the way.

42:26.360 --> 42:29.160
It's just getting more and more like the moderns.

42:29.160 --> 42:30.800
So the question is, what happened

42:30.800 --> 42:32.600
between three and 400,000 years ago

42:32.600 --> 42:34.720
to produce homo sapiens?

42:34.720 --> 42:38.120
And I think we have a pretty good answer now.

42:38.120 --> 42:40.160
And the answer comes from violence.

42:40.160 --> 42:44.120
And the story begins by focusing on this question.

42:44.120 --> 42:49.120
Why is it that in the human species,

42:49.120 --> 42:51.560
we are unique among all primates

42:51.560 --> 42:55.560
in not having an alpha male in any group

42:56.960 --> 42:59.640
in the sense that what we don't have

42:59.640 --> 43:03.840
is an alpha male who personally beats up every other male?

43:05.280 --> 43:10.280
And the answer that has been portrayed

43:11.560 --> 43:15.960
most richly by Christopher Boehm

43:15.960 --> 43:18.760
and whose work I've elaborated on

43:18.800 --> 43:23.800
is that only in humans do you have a system

43:24.680 --> 43:28.640
by which any male who tries to bully others

43:29.840 --> 43:33.280
and become the alpha equivalent to an alpha gorilla

43:33.280 --> 43:35.280
or an alpha chimpanzee or an alpha bonobo

43:35.280 --> 43:37.600
or an alpha baboon or anything like that,

43:37.600 --> 43:39.640
any male who tries to do that in humans

43:40.640 --> 43:44.520
gets taken down by a coalition of beta males.

43:46.800 --> 43:47.960
That coalition?

43:48.160 --> 43:51.560
I guess it's a really good picture of human society.

43:51.560 --> 43:52.880
Yes, I like it.

43:52.880 --> 43:55.680
Okay, so and that's the way all our societies work now.

43:55.680 --> 43:56.520
Yes.

43:56.520 --> 43:58.720
Because individuals try and be alpha

43:58.720 --> 44:00.080
and then they get taken out.

44:00.080 --> 44:02.040
Yeah, I mean, we don't usually think of ourselves

44:02.040 --> 44:06.520
as beta males, but yes, I suppose that's what democracy is.

44:06.520 --> 44:08.440
Exactly, yes, exactly.

44:09.880 --> 44:14.600
Okay, so at some point alpha males get taken out.

44:14.600 --> 44:16.840
Well, what alpha males are are males

44:16.840 --> 44:20.640
who respond with high reactive violence

44:20.640 --> 44:22.760
to any challenge to their status.

44:22.760 --> 44:25.120
You see it all the time in primates.

44:25.120 --> 44:28.080
Some beta male thinks he's getting strong

44:28.080 --> 44:31.720
and maturing in wisdom and so on

44:31.720 --> 44:35.920
and he refuses to kowtow to the alpha male

44:35.920 --> 44:39.400
and the alpha male comes straight in and charges at him.

44:39.400 --> 44:41.680
Or maybe he'll just wait for a few minutes

44:41.680 --> 44:44.360
or over and then take an opportunity to attack him.

44:45.200 --> 44:50.200
All of these primates have got a high tendency

44:51.320 --> 44:53.200
for reactive aggression

44:53.200 --> 44:56.400
and that enables the possibility of alpha males.

44:56.400 --> 44:58.600
We don't, we have this great reduction

44:58.600 --> 45:00.400
as I talked about earlier.

45:00.400 --> 45:04.000
And the question is when did that reduction happen?

45:04.000 --> 45:08.520
Well, cut to the famous experiments

45:08.520 --> 45:12.280
by the Russian biologist Dmitry Believ

45:12.320 --> 45:16.320
who tried domesticating wild animals.

45:17.600 --> 45:19.920
When you domesticate wild animals,

45:19.920 --> 45:23.760
what you're doing is reducing reactive aggression.

45:24.680 --> 45:28.240
You are selecting those individuals to breed

45:28.240 --> 45:31.960
who are most willing to be approached by a human

45:31.960 --> 45:34.360
or by another member of their own species

45:34.360 --> 45:39.360
and are least likely to erupt in a reactive aggression.

45:40.040 --> 45:42.960
And you only have to do that for a few generations

45:42.960 --> 45:47.120
to discover that there are changes in the skull

45:47.120 --> 45:50.720
and those changes consist of

45:53.280 --> 45:56.400
shorter face, smaller teeth,

45:56.400 --> 45:59.360
a reduced maleness,

45:59.360 --> 46:01.840
the males become increasingly female-like

46:03.160 --> 46:04.920
and reduced brain size.

46:06.400 --> 46:08.440
Well, the changes that are characteristic

46:08.480 --> 46:10.440
of domesticated animals in general,

46:10.440 --> 46:11.920
compared to wild animals,

46:11.920 --> 46:13.920
are all found in homo sapiens

46:13.920 --> 46:16.680
compared to our early ancestors.

46:16.680 --> 46:18.440
So it's a very strong signal

46:18.440 --> 46:21.080
that when we first see homo sapiens,

46:21.080 --> 46:22.960
what we're seeing is evidence

46:22.960 --> 46:26.280
of a reduction in reactive aggression.

46:26.280 --> 46:29.400
And that suggests that what's happening with homo sapiens

46:29.400 --> 46:32.080
is that that is the point

46:32.080 --> 46:35.520
at which there is selection against the alpha males.

46:35.520 --> 46:39.320
And therefore, the way in which the selection happened

46:39.320 --> 46:41.480
would have been the way it happens today.

46:41.480 --> 46:42.920
The beta males take them out.

46:44.200 --> 46:47.520
So I think that homo sapiens is a species

46:47.520 --> 46:52.520
characterized by the suppression of reactive aggression

46:53.320 --> 46:55.400
as a kind of incidental consequence

46:55.400 --> 46:58.520
of the suppression of the alpha male.

46:58.520 --> 47:00.800
And the story of our species

47:00.800 --> 47:04.160
is the story of how the beta males took charge.

47:05.760 --> 47:07.920
And have been responsible

47:07.920 --> 47:12.000
for the generation of a new kind of human.

47:13.400 --> 47:15.040
And incidentally,

47:16.400 --> 47:21.160
for imposing on the society

47:21.160 --> 47:24.240
a new set of values.

47:24.240 --> 47:26.720
Because when those beta males discovered

47:26.720 --> 47:29.920
that they could take out the previous alpha male

47:29.920 --> 47:31.040
and continue to do so,

47:31.040 --> 47:32.200
because in every generation,

47:32.200 --> 47:33.440
there'll always be some male who says,

47:34.080 --> 47:36.200
maybe I'll become the alpha male.

47:36.200 --> 47:38.280
So they just keep chopping them down.

47:39.600 --> 47:40.600
In discovering that,

47:40.600 --> 47:42.400
they also obviously discovered

47:42.400 --> 47:44.400
that they could kill anybody in the group.

47:45.400 --> 47:47.480
Females, young males,

47:48.440 --> 47:52.000
anybody who didn't follow their values.

47:52.960 --> 47:55.280
And so this story is one of,

47:56.160 --> 47:59.560
one in which the males of our species,

47:59.560 --> 48:01.480
and these would be the breeding males,

48:02.480 --> 48:06.800
have been able to impose their values on everybody else.

48:06.800 --> 48:08.120
And there was two kind of values.

48:08.120 --> 48:10.040
There's one kind of value is things that are good

48:10.040 --> 48:12.400
for the group, like thou shalt not murder.

48:13.920 --> 48:16.120
And the other kind of value is things

48:16.120 --> 48:18.120
that are good for the males.

48:19.480 --> 48:21.240
Such as, hey, guess what?

48:21.240 --> 48:23.440
When good food comes in, males get it first.

48:23.440 --> 48:24.280
Yes.

48:25.320 --> 48:28.520
So I mean, it's fascinating that that kind of set of ideals

48:28.520 --> 48:31.960
could outcompete the others.

48:33.000 --> 48:35.400
Do you have a sense of why,

48:35.400 --> 48:37.480
or maybe you can comment on Neanderthals

48:37.480 --> 48:39.240
and all the other early humans.

48:39.240 --> 48:44.240
Why did homo sapiens come to succeed and flourish

48:44.360 --> 48:45.680
and all the other ones,

48:45.680 --> 48:49.120
all the other branches of evolution died out?

48:50.600 --> 48:51.720
Or got murdered out?

48:51.720 --> 48:56.040
Nowadays when homo sapiens, meets homo sapiens,

48:56.040 --> 48:59.200
and we don't know each other initially,

48:59.200 --> 49:00.640
then conflict breaks out

49:00.640 --> 49:05.640
and the more militarily able group wins.

49:06.760 --> 49:09.120
You know, we've seen that everywhere

49:09.120 --> 49:13.280
throughout the age of exploration and throughout history.

49:14.320 --> 49:16.160
So I'm rather surprised, you know,

49:16.160 --> 49:20.480
the conventional wisdom that you see nowadays

49:20.480 --> 49:24.400
in contemporary anthropology is very reluctant

49:24.400 --> 49:28.120
to point to success in warfare

49:28.120 --> 49:32.480
as the reason why sapiens wiped out Neanderthals

49:32.480 --> 49:35.560
within about 3,000 years of the sapiens

49:35.560 --> 49:38.720
coming into Europe 43,000 years ago.

49:39.760 --> 49:42.280
And people are much more inclined to say,

49:42.280 --> 49:45.240
well, the Neanderthals were at low population density,

49:45.240 --> 49:50.240
so they just couldn't survive the demographic sweep

49:51.240 --> 49:54.040
or the disease came in.

49:54.040 --> 49:56.600
You know, maybe those things might have been important,

49:56.600 --> 50:00.040
but far and away, the most obvious possibility

50:00.040 --> 50:05.040
is that sapiens were just powerful.

50:06.760 --> 50:09.360
They had, everyone agrees they had larger groups.

50:10.400 --> 50:11.640
They had better weapons.

50:12.600 --> 50:15.880
They had projectile weapons, bows and arrows

50:15.880 --> 50:20.240
to judge from the little microlyth, bits of flake,

50:22.040 --> 50:23.560
which the Neanderthals didn't.

50:24.840 --> 50:29.040
You know, nowadays there's evidence of interbreeding,

50:29.040 --> 50:30.440
quite extensive interbreeding

50:30.440 --> 50:33.160
between sapiens and Neanderthals,

50:33.160 --> 50:35.200
as well as with some other groups.

50:35.200 --> 50:37.280
And sometimes people say, well, you know,

50:37.280 --> 50:38.560
so they loved each other.

50:38.560 --> 50:40.480
They made love, not war.

50:40.480 --> 50:42.480
I think they made love and war.

50:42.760 --> 50:46.520
And, you know, it wouldn't necessarily mean too loving.

50:46.520 --> 50:49.240
I mean, if you just follow through

50:49.240 --> 50:51.680
from typical ethnographies nowadays

50:51.680 --> 50:55.400
of when dominant groups meet subordinate groups,

50:55.400 --> 50:56.840
they didn't know each other,

50:56.840 --> 51:00.520
then you can imagine that Neanderthal females

51:00.520 --> 51:02.400
would essentially be captured

51:02.400 --> 51:05.360
and taken into sapiens groups.

51:07.120 --> 51:11.200
Maybe you can comment on this cautiously

51:12.200 --> 51:16.200
and eloquently, what's the role of sexual violence

51:16.200 --> 51:18.000
in human evolution?

51:18.000 --> 51:21.320
Because you mentioned taking Neanderthal females.

51:21.320 --> 51:23.760
You've also mentioned that some of these rules

51:23.760 --> 51:28.640
are defined by the male side of the society.

51:28.640 --> 51:31.440
What's the role of sexual violence in this story?

51:32.960 --> 51:34.680
I think you've got to distinguish between groups

51:34.680 --> 51:35.680
and within groups.

51:36.680 --> 51:41.680
And, you know, I think the world has been slowly waking up

51:43.280 --> 51:46.040
over the last several decades

51:46.040 --> 51:51.040
to the fact that sexual violence is routine in war.

51:52.680 --> 51:57.680
And that to me says that it's just another example

51:58.760 --> 52:01.400
of power corrupts because, you know,

52:01.400 --> 52:06.400
when frustrated, scared, elated soldiers

52:09.320 --> 52:12.840
come upon females in a group

52:12.840 --> 52:16.400
that there's been essential dehumanization of,

52:17.440 --> 52:20.600
then they get carried away by opportunity.

52:21.760 --> 52:25.160
It is not always possible to argue

52:25.160 --> 52:28.600
that this is adaptive nowadays

52:28.600 --> 52:31.200
because, you know, you get lots and lots of stories

52:31.200 --> 52:36.200
of women being abused to the point of being killed.

52:38.760 --> 52:41.200
She'll be gang raped and then killed.

52:41.200 --> 52:46.200
There's lots of terrible cases of that reported

52:46.200 --> 52:47.800
from all sorts of different wars.

52:49.600 --> 52:54.600
But you can see that that could build on a pattern

52:54.920 --> 52:58.160
that would have been adaptive if happening

52:58.160 --> 53:01.560
in under sort of much less extreme circumstances.

53:02.360 --> 53:05.240
You know, the war is very extreme nowadays

53:05.240 --> 53:07.520
in the sense that you get battles

53:07.520 --> 53:11.320
in which people are sent by a military hierarchy

53:11.320 --> 53:14.200
into a war situation in which they do not feel

53:14.200 --> 53:16.520
what hunters and gatherers would typically have felt

53:16.520 --> 53:18.680
which would have been that if we attack,

53:18.680 --> 53:22.000
we have an excellent chance of getting away with it.

53:22.000 --> 53:25.280
Nowadays, you know, you're sent in across the Somme

53:25.280 --> 53:27.840
or whatever it is and there's a very high chance

53:27.840 --> 53:30.360
you will be killed and that's totally unnatural

53:30.360 --> 53:33.160
and a novel evolutionary experience, I think.

53:34.880 --> 53:37.600
Then there's sexual coercion within groups

53:37.600 --> 53:42.600
and so that takes various kinds of forms, you know,

53:43.360 --> 53:44.800
but nowadays, of course,

53:44.800 --> 53:47.040
I think people recognize increasingly

53:47.040 --> 53:52.040
that the principal form of sexual intimidation

53:53.040 --> 53:57.120
and rape occurs within relationships.

53:58.440 --> 54:03.440
It's not stranger rape that is really statistically important.

54:03.440 --> 54:04.680
There's much more.

54:05.720 --> 54:10.720
What happens behind the walls of a bedroom

54:12.080 --> 54:14.960
where people have been living for some time

54:14.960 --> 54:19.960
and just two sort of thoughts and observations about this.

54:20.960 --> 54:25.960
One is that it may seem odd that males should be,

54:32.160 --> 54:34.920
should think it a good idea, as it were,

54:34.920 --> 54:37.840
to impose themselves sexually

54:37.840 --> 54:40.200
on someone with whom they have a relationship.

54:41.560 --> 54:46.040
But what they're doing is intimidating someone

54:46.040 --> 54:49.400
in a relationship in which the relative power

54:49.400 --> 54:52.880
in the relationship has continuing significance

54:52.880 --> 54:54.400
for a long time.

54:54.400 --> 54:58.880
And that power probably goes well beyond just the sexual.

54:58.880 --> 55:01.960
You know, it's to do with domestic relationships,

55:01.960 --> 55:06.240
it's to do with the man getting his own way all the way.

55:06.240 --> 55:09.880
It's power dynamics and the sexual aggression

55:09.880 --> 55:13.240
is one of the tools to regain power or gain power

55:13.240 --> 55:14.920
or gain more power and that kind of thing.

55:14.920 --> 55:16.720
Yeah, exactly.

55:16.720 --> 55:21.720
And in that respect, it's worth noting that

55:22.360 --> 55:25.720
although this wasn't appreciated for some time,

55:25.720 --> 55:28.360
it's emerging that in a bunch of primates

55:28.360 --> 55:33.360
you have somewhat parallel kinds of sexual intimidation

55:35.040 --> 55:37.840
where males will target particular females

55:37.840 --> 55:41.320
even in a group in which the norm is for females

55:41.320 --> 55:43.520
to mate with multiple males.

55:43.520 --> 55:45.960
But each male will target a particular female

55:46.000 --> 55:49.640
and the more he is aggressive towards her

55:49.640 --> 55:53.240
then the more she conforms to his wishes

55:53.240 --> 55:55.320
when he wants to mate.

55:55.320 --> 55:58.000
So a long-term pattern of sexual intimidation.

55:58.920 --> 56:00.400
So there's that aspect.

56:00.400 --> 56:04.800
The other aspect I would just note is that males

56:06.720 --> 56:10.240
get away with a lot compared to females

56:10.240 --> 56:13.720
in any kind of intersexual conflict.

56:14.560 --> 56:19.560
So the punishment, here's one example of this,

56:19.960 --> 56:23.480
the punishment for a husband killing a wife

56:23.480 --> 56:25.640
has always been much less than the punishment

56:25.640 --> 56:27.160
for a wife killing a husband.

56:29.960 --> 56:32.200
And you see similar sorts of things

56:32.200 --> 56:37.200
in terms of the punishments for adultery and so on.

56:38.760 --> 56:43.000
I bring this up in the context of males

56:43.000 --> 56:46.840
sexually intimidating their partners,

56:46.840 --> 56:49.240
be it wives or whoever,

56:50.720 --> 56:54.400
because it's a reminder that it's basically

56:54.400 --> 56:57.840
a patriarchal world that we have come from,

56:57.840 --> 57:02.120
a patriarchal world in which male alliances

57:02.120 --> 57:06.280
tend to support males and take advantage of the fact

57:06.280 --> 57:09.800
that they have political power at the expense of females.

57:09.800 --> 57:12.040
And I would say that that all goes back

57:12.080 --> 57:14.880
to what happened three to 400,000 years ago

57:14.880 --> 57:16.760
when the beta males took charge

57:16.760 --> 57:19.240
and they started imposing their own norms

57:19.240 --> 57:22.600
on society as a whole and they've continued to do so.

57:22.600 --> 57:26.200
And we now look at ourselves and Jordan Peterson says,

57:26.200 --> 57:28.840
we are not a patriarchal society.

57:28.840 --> 57:33.080
Well, it's true that the laws try and make it even-handed

57:33.080 --> 57:35.480
nowadays between males and females.

57:35.480 --> 57:38.920
But obviously we are patriarchal de facto

57:38.920 --> 57:43.920
because society still in many ways supports men

57:45.360 --> 57:48.120
better than it supports women in these sorts of conflicts.

